article.description:
The Philadelphia 76ers needed big numbers from
their backups, but it was the New York Knicks' reserves who came
through.
article.headline: Sixers lose out on chance to close gap atop East
article.linkText: Knicks' reserves keep Sixers from gaining ground
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- The Philadelphia 76ers needed big numbers from their backups, but it was the New York Knicks' reserves who came through. Allan Houston scored 25 points, and Howard Eisley added 18 as New York beat Philadelphia 108-103 Friday night. Latrell Sprewell played tough defense on 76ers guard Allen Iverson and scored eight of his 16 points in the fourth quarter to lead New York down the stretch. Shandon Anderson added 15 points off the bench as the Knicks got solid minutes from all 12 players. ''Everyone on this team showed we want to finish the season strong and get some momentum for next year,'' Houston said. ''Going into next season we want to be known as a team that can compete in the Eastern Conference.'' Iverson had 20 points and 11 assists for Philadelphia, which had won two consecutive but was again without starting forwards Derrick Coleman and Keith Van Horn. But Philadelphia's star guard scored only four points in the fourth quarter, and the 76ers failed to gain ground in the Eastern Conference playoff race. New Jersey and Detroit remained a game ahead of the 76ers after the Nets lost to Chicago and the Pistons lost to New Orleans. ''They're not going to the playoffs, so they have nothing to lose,'' Iverson said of the Knicks. ''We have everything to lose. ''Jersey just lost, and we could have done a lot of things as far as seeding, but coulda, woulda, shoulda, you know?'' Eric Snow scored 18 points for the 76ers and Kenny Thomas added 15 points and 10 rebounds, but had a shot blocked by Clarence Weatherspoon with 29 seconds left. Sprewell's two free throws moments later put New York up 102-96. Philadelphia, which outrebounded New York 37-27, never got closer than three points the rest of the way. The Knicks played tough defense against the short-handed 76ers, resulting in three shot-clock violations and forcing Philadelphia to shoot with the clock winding down several times. ''They had a lot of guys come in and play well off the bench,'' Philadelphia coach Larry Brown said. ''We played last night and our bench was so short. ... The best thing is we never stopped trying and we made it interesting.'' Lavor Postell, the seldom-used guard from St. John's, sparked the Knicks in the fourth quarter, scoring six consecutive points as New York's starters rested. With 5:45 left, New York coach Don Chaney reinserted his starting lineup, and the depleted 76ers couldn't keep up. ''They haven't seen me, but they know I can play now,'' Postell said. Iverson had a pair of turnovers with less than three minutes left, and Sprewell hit a 3-pointer to put the Knicks up 96-91 with 2:55 left. Houston followed with a jumper to give the Knicks a seven-point lead, their largest of the game, but Philadelphia cut it to three when Snow hit a layup after Iverson missed a 3-pointer. The Knicks flirted with the playoffs this year after a disappointing 2-10 start, and Friday night outplayed the third-best team in the Eastern Conference. ''We know we can play with anyone in the East,'' Sprewell said. ''We were right there until there were only four games left in the season. That says a lot about our character.'' Game notes
With 22 seconds left, Sprewell walked over to Philadelphia's bench and wished the 76ers good luck in the playoffs. ... With the Knicks officially out of the playoff chase, Chaney said he'd play little-used guards Frank Williams and Postell and forward Lee Nailon more often in New York's final games. ... Coleman, who has a left quadriceps strain and a bruised left hand, did not shoot before the game, but Van Horn, who has a strained left foot, did. Brown did not expect either to play Sunday against New Orleans. ... The Knicks evened the season series at two games apiece.
